data.content:
Here are the modern MSTest assertion replacements:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    Assert.HasCount(users, 3);
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive));
    var admin = users.Single(u => u.Role == "Admin");
    Assert.IsNotNull(admin);
}
```

Key improvements:

| Original | Replacement | Why |
|----------|-------------|-----|
| `Assert.IsTrue(users.Count > 0)` | `Assert.HasCount(users, 3)` | Redundant if you already assert count == 3 |
| `Assert.IsTrue(users.Count() == 3)` | `Assert.HasCount(users, 3)` | Better failure message (shows actual count) |
| `Assert.IsTrue(admin != null)` | `Assert.IsNotNull(admin)` | Clearer intent and failure message |

Other useful collection assertions in MSTest 3.x+:

- **`Assert.HasCount(collection, expected)`** – exact count
- **`Assert.IsNotNull(obj)`** – null check
- **`CollectionAssert.Contains(collection, item)`** – membership
- **`CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreNotNull(collection)`** – no nulls
- **`CollectionAssert.AreEquivalent(expected, actual)`** – same items, any order

For the `users.All(u => u.IsActive)` check, `Assert.IsTrue` is reasonable since there's no built-in predicate-based collection assert, though you could use:

```csharp
foreach (var user in users)
    Assert.IsTrue(user.IsActive, $"User {user.Name} is not active");
```

This gives per-item failure messages instead of a generic "expected true, got false."
